# Claude Code Insights

9 sessions total · 8 analyzed · 122 messages · 54h · 12 commits
2026-03-25 to 2026-03-30

## At a Glance

**What's working:** You're doing something genuinely powerful by codifying your entire dev workflow into reusable Claude skills — that spec→plan→TDD→verify→simplify→review→learn pipeline is the kind of compound investment that pays off every session. You're also keeping Claude tightly in your development loop, using it to scaffold full-stack projects and validate changes in real time rather than just generating code in isolation. See _Impressive Things You Did_.

**What's hindering you:** On Claude's side, it has a tendency to ignore context you've already provided (like web-searching instead of using a URL you gave it) and to produce the wrong type of output entirely — a troubleshooting doc when you wanted a reusable prompt, three test cases when you wanted one. On your side, frontend debugging rounds (especially CSS and browser API issues) are eating a lot of time, partly because complex UI features are being tackled as single large requests rather than broken into smaller testable steps. See _Where Things Go Wrong_.

**Quick wins to try:** Since you've already built 7+ skills, add your skill structure and conventions to your CLAUDE.md so Claude doesn't need re-guidance each session — this should cut the friction you hit when creating new skills. Also try delegating multi-round debugging (like that drag-and-drop saga) to sub-agents via `/task`, keeping your main session focused on higher-level decisions. See _Features to Try_.

**Ambitious workflows:** Your TDD skill pipeline is a strong candidate for full autonomy soon — imagine Claude running the entire spec→implement→verify→simplify loop against your test suite without check-ins, only surfacing when tests stay red. Your monorepo work could also benefit from parallel agents handling frontend and backend scaffolding simultaneously, each with tightly scoped context that avoids the kind of "wrong approach" detours you've been hitting. See _On the Horizon_.

